The Ahmed Kathrada Foundation has on Tuesday announced the passing of ANC stalwart Khatrada (87) at the Donald Gordon Hospital in Johannesburg.Kathrada passed away after a short period of illness, following surgery to the brain.Executive Director Neeshan Balton said: This is great loss to the ANC, the broader liberation movement and South Africa as a whole. Internationally, he was staunch in his support for the Palestinian struggle. Kathy was an inspiration to millions in different parts of the world.&#8221;Kathrada has had an illustrious political career having served between 1994 and 1999 as the parliamentary counsellor to late President Nelson Mandela.He was born on 21 August 1929 in rural Schweizer-Reneke and was introduced to politics as a young boy when he joined a non-racial youth club run by the Young Communist League.At the tender age of 17, Kathrada participated in the 1946 Passive Resistance Campaign led by the South African Indian Congress. He was part of 2000 resisters who were arrested and imprisoned for defying a law that discriminated against Indian South Africans.Kathrada Foundation Chairperson, Derek Hanekom, was overcome with emotion saying he has lost a revolutionary mentor and dear friend . Comrade Kathy was a gentle, humane and humble soul. He was a determined revolutionary who gave his entire life to the liberation struggle in our country, said Hanekom.Kathrada will be buried according to Muslim religious rights, details of which will be made publicly available in due course.He spent 26 years and 3 months in prison, 18 of which were on Robben Island. In 1982, Mandela, Sisulu, Kathrada, Mhlaba and Mlangeni were transferred to Pollsmoor Prison in Cape Town.While in prison he obtained four university degrees, namely, BA (in History and Criminology), B Bibliography (in African Politics and Library Science), BA Honours (History) and BA Honours (African Politics).Fellow Robben Island prisoner, Laloo Isu Chiba (86) said that his comrade s death has left a deep vacuum in his life. I have worked with Kathy for over sixty years. He has been my strength in prison, my guide in political life and my pillar of strength in the most difficult moments of my life. Now he is gone, said Chiba.TNA Reporter